in the 1970s, where the MVC (Model-View-Controller) pattern was invented.
On the industry side, Microsoft has MFC and WPF, Java has AWT and Swing,
and Apple has Cocoa.
%
On the minimal end, Nuklear is a single-header-file GUI library in~C,
showing that a widget toolkit does not need to be huge.
[[libpanel]] sits squarely in this minimalist tradition.

\section{Getting started}
\label{sec:getting-started}

%claude:
To play with [[libpanel]], you will first need to install
the \plan fork used in \principia (see \urlinstall).
Once installed, you can compile and run a small test program
called [[hellopanel.c]] (described in more detail in Chapter~\ref{chap:overview})
with the following commands:

\begin{verbatim}
1   % cd /lib_gui/libpanel/tests
2   % mk hellopanel
3   5c -c hellopanel.c
4   5l -o hellopanel hellopanel.5
5   % hellopanel
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
Line~2 runs [[mk]] to compile [[hellopanel.c]].
The \plan C compiler [[5c]] produces an object file [[hellopanel.5]],
and the linker [[5l]] produces the executable.
%
Line~5 runs the program, which opens a window containing
a ``Hello, world!'' label and a ``done'' button.
Clicking the button exits the program.
This is the [[libpanel]] equivalent of a ``hello world.''

