\section{Software architecture}

% plxxx
% plinitxxx
% pl_drawxxx
% pl_hitxxx

%claude:
Figure~\ref{fig:dataflow} describes the main data flow of [[libpanel]], whereas
Figure~\ref{fig:controlflow} describes the main control flow.

\begin{figure}[!tbp]\centering
\begin{verbatim}
   Application                          libpanel
  +-------------------+          +---------------------+
  |                   |          |                      |
  |  plframe(nil,...) +--------->+  Panel tree          |
  |  pllabel(root,..) |          |   root               |
  |  plbutton(root,..)|          |   |-- label          |
  |                   |          |   `-- button          |
  |                   |          |                      |
  |  plpack(root, r)  +--------->+  Layout pass         |
  |                   |          |   sizereq (bottom-up) |
  |                   |          |   setrect (top-down)  |
  |                   |          |                      |
  |  pldraw(root, b)  +--------->+  Draw pass           |
  |                   |          |   (top-down)          |
  |                   |          |                      |
  |  event(&e)        |  Mouse   |                      |
  |  plmouse(root, m) +--------->+  Hit dispatch        |
  |                   |          |   (top-down)          |
  |                   |<---------+  Callback             |
  +-------------------+          +---------------------+
\end{verbatim}
\caption{Data flow diagram of [[libpanel]].}\label{fig:dataflow}
\end{figure}

%claude:
As shown in Figure~\ref{fig:dataflow}, the application builds a tree
of [<Panel>] widgets using constructors like [<plframe()>], [<pllabel()>],
and [<plbutton()>]. It then calls [<plpack()>] to compute the layout
and [<pldraw()>] to render the tree. During the event loop,
mouse events are dispatched into the tree via [<plmouse()>], which
finds the target widget and triggers its callback.

