                   +-----v----+
                   | pl_hit() |
                   +-----+----+
                         |
                +--------+--------+
                |                 |
         +------v------+   +-----v-------+
         |pl_hitbutton()|  |pl_hitentry()|  ...
         +------+------+   +-------------+
                |
         +------v------+
         |  callback   |  (e.g., done())
         +-------------+
\end{verbatim}
\caption{Control flow diagram of [[libpanel]].}\label{fig:controlflow}
\end{figure}

%claude:
Figure~\ref{fig:controlflow} shows the two main flows triggered
by the application.
%
The first flow is triggered by [<eresized()>] (either at startup or
when the window is resized): [<plpack()>] runs the two-pass layout
algorithm---[<pl_sizereq()>] walks the tree bottom-up to collect
size requests, then [<pl_setrect()>] walks top-down to assign
rectangles. After layout, [<pldraw()>] walks the tree top-down,
calling [<pl_draw()>] on each widget, which dispatches to the
type-specific drawing function (e.g., [<pl_drawlabel()>],
[<pl_drawbutton()>]).
%
The second flow is triggered by a mouse event: [<plmouse()>]
calls [<pl_hit()>] to find which widget contains the mouse
coordinates, then dispatches to the type-specific hit handler
(e.g., [<pl_hitbutton()>]), which may invoke the application's
callback.

%claude:
[[libpanel]] uses a consistent naming convention that reveals
its architecture. Public functions use the [[pl]] prefix:
[<plinit()>], [<pldraw()>], [<plpack()>], [<plmouse()>], [<plfree()>].
Widget constructors also use [[pl]]: [<pllabel()>], [<plbutton()>],
[<plframe()>], [<pllist()>], etc.
%
Internal functions (not meant for application programmers) use
the [[pl_]] prefix with an underscore:
[<pl_draw()>] is the internal draw dispatcher,
[<pl_hit()>] is the internal mouse-hit dispatcher,
[<pl_sizereq()>] and [<pl_setrect()>] are the two layout passes.
%
Each widget type provides its own implementations of these
internal methods. For instance, the button widget provides
[<pl_drawbutton()>] and [<pl_hitbutton()>]. These are stored
as function pointers in the [<Panel>] structure, enabling
{polymorphic dispatch}: calling [<pl_draw()>] on any widget
automatically calls the right type-specific drawing function.

