\section{Book structure}

%claude:
The rest of this book follows the architecture of [[libpanel]].
%
Chapter~\ref{chap:core-ds} presents the core data structures, primarily the
[[Panel]] structure and the widget tree.
Chapter~\ref{chap:main} covers initialization.
Chapter~\ref{chap:drawing} covers drawing---how [[pldraw()]] walks the tree
and renders each widget.
Chapter~\ref{chap:events} covers event handling---how [[plmouse()]] dispatches
mouse events to the right widget.
Chapter~\ref{chap:layout} covers layout---the two-pass algorithm of
[[plpack()]].
%
The following chapters then go through the individual widget types:
basic widgets (label, entry, button, slider, canvas),
composite widgets (frame, group),
scrollable widgets (list, scroll bar),
menu widgets (popup, pull-down, menu bar),
and text widgets (message, edit, text view).
%
The final chapters cover advanced topics and the conclusion.

%###############################################################################

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Core Data Structures}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:core-ds}

\begin{verse}
\begin{flushright}
  {\it Show me your code and conceal your data structures, and I shall
    continue to be mystified. Show me your data structures, and I
    won't usually need your code; it'll be obvious.\\
    ~\\
    Fred Brooks}
\end{flushright}
\end{verse}


%toc:
%claude:
In this chapter, I will present the core data structures of [[libpanel]]:
the [<Panel>] structure (the central widget type),
the [<Icon>] type,
and the {layout style} constants that control how widgets are
arranged within their parent ([[PACK]], [[PLACE]], [[FILL]]).

%claude:
All of these are defined in the [[panel.h]] header file.
The [<Panel>] structure is the heart of the library ---
every widget, from a simple label to a complex text editor,
is represented by this single structure.

\section{[[Panel]]}
\l widget really

%claude:
The [<Panel>] structure is the universal widget type in [[libpanel]].
Every widget --- whether a label, a button, a text entry, or a scrollbar ---
is a [<Panel>].
%
The overview chunk below shows its overall shape:
the two key fields visible here are [[Rectangle r]], which defines
where the widget is positioned on screen, and [[Image *b]],
which is the drawing surface.
The rest of the fields and methods are defined gradually
in the following subsections.

<<struct [[Panel]]>>=
struct Panel{
    // public

    Rectangle r;					/* where the Panel goes */

    <<[[Panel]] padding fields>>
    <<[[Panel]] fixed size field>>
    <<[[Panel]] user-specific fields>>

    /* private below */

    Image *b;					/* where we're drawn */
    <<[[Panel]] widget-specific data>>
    <<[[Panel]] layout fields>>
    <<[[Panel]] debugging fields>>
    <<[[Panel]] other fields>>

    // methods
    <<[[Panel]] main methods>>
    <<[[Panel]] packing methods>>
    <<[[Panel]] other methods>>

    // Extra
    <<[[Panel]] extra fields>>
};
@

% In the rest I will use the term widget instead of panel.

%Panel.r is set by plpack() and Panel.b is set by pldraw()

%claude:
Note that [[Panel.r]] (the rectangle) and [[Panel.b]] (the drawing surface)
are not set at construction time --- they are filled in later by
[<plpack()>] and [<pldraw()>] respectively.
This two-phase initialization reflects the separation between
layout and drawing described in Chapter~\ref{chap:overview}.

%ctor
%claude:
The constructor [<pl_newpanel()>] takes a parent widget and
an [[ndata]] size parameter (explained later in
Section~\ref{sec:widget-data}).
It allocates a [<Panel>], links it into the parent's child list,
and sets safe defaults for all fields.

<<function [[pl_newpanel]]>>=
Panel *pl_newpanel(Panel *parent, int ndata){
    Panel *v;

    <<[[pl_newpanel()]] sanity check if can create child on [[parent]]>>
    v=pl_emalloc(sizeof(Panel));

    <<[[pl_newpanel()]] set tree fields>>
    <<[[pl_newpanel()]] set widget-specific data fields>>
    <<[[pl_newpanel()]] set other fields>>
  
    <<[[pl_newpanel()]] set default methods>>

    return v;
}
@
%pad: I reordered the assignments

%See appendix for pl_emalloc

<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set other fields>>=
v->r=Rect(0,0,0,0);
v->b=nil;
@
%dup: Panel.b set by draw, and Panel.r by packing?

%dtor
%claude:
The destructor [<plfree()>] recursively frees a widget and all
its children.
The chunks it references are defined in the following subsections
as each field group is introduced.

<<function [[plfree]]>>=
void plfree(Panel *p){
    <<[[plfree]] locals>>

    if(p==nil)
        return;
    <<[[plfree()]] if [[plkbfocus]]>>
    <<[[plfree()]] free the children>>
    <<[[plfree()]] free the widget-specific data>>
    free(p);
}
@

\subsection{Widget flags}

%claude:
The [[flags]] field is an [[int]] used as a {bitset}.
Different bits encode different properties: whether the widget is
a leaf, whether it is invisible, and --- most importantly ---
the layout style (see Section~\ref{sec:layout-styles}).

<<[[Panel]] other fields>>=
// LEAF | INVIS | ...
int flags;					/* position flags, see below */
@

<<constant [[NOFLAG]]>>=
#define NOFLAG 0
@
%pad: I introduced that

<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set other fields>>=
v->flags=NOFLAG;
@

\subsection{A tree of widgets}

%claude:
Widgets form a tree: each [<Panel>] can have children,
and each child knows its parent.
The children are stored as a singly linked list
(via [[next]] pointers), with [[child]] pointing to the first child
and [[echild]] pointing to the last (for efficient appending).
This is the classic {child-sibling} tree representation:
[[child]] goes ``down'' to the first child,
[[next]] goes ``right'' to the next sibling.

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  Example: a frame with three children (label, entry, button)

                      +-------+
           .parent--->| frame |<---.parent--------------.parent
           |          +-------+    |                     |
           |  .child |             |             .echild |
           |         v             |                     v
           | +-------+  .next  +-------+  .next  +--------+  .next
           '-| label | ------> | entry | ------> | button | ------> nil
             +-------+         +-------+         +--------+
\end{verbatim}

<<[[Panel]] extra fields>>=
// option<list<ref_own<Panel>>> (next = Panel.next, tail = Panel.echild)
Panel *child;
@

<<[[Panel]] extra fields>>=
// list<ref<Panel>> (head = Panel.child)
Panel *next;					/* It's a list! */
@

<<[[Panel]] extra fields>>=
// option<ref<Panel>>
Panel *echild;
@
% to quickly add to the end

<<[[Panel]] extra fields>>=
// option<ref<Panel>>
Panel *parent; 			/* No, it's a tree! */
@




% parent is parameter. Most widgets constructors take the parent
% as a parameter to "pack" it inside.
%claude:
Insertion appends the new widget at the end of the parent's child list,
using [[echild]] as a tail pointer to avoid traversing the entire list.
This means children are laid out in the order they were created,
which is usually the order the programmer wants.

<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set tree fields>>=
v->next=nil;
v->child=nil;
v->echild=nil;

v->parent=parent;
//add_list(v, parent->child)
if(parent){
    if(parent->child==nil)
        parent->child=v;
    else
        parent->echild->next=v;
    parent->echild=v;
}
@

<<[[plfree]] locals>>=
Panel *cp, *ncp;
@
<<[[plfree()]] free the children>>=
for(cp=p->child;cp;cp=ncp){
    ncp=cp->next;
    plfree(cp);
}
@



%claude:
Leaf widgets (labels, buttons) cannot have children.
The [[LEAF]] flag enforces this at construction time:
[<pl_newpanel()>] refuses to create a child on a leaf widget.

<<constant [[LEAF]]>>=
#define	LEAF	0x10000		/* newpanel will refuse to attach children */
@
%ex a label can not have children.

<<[[pl_newpanel()]] sanity check if can create child on [[parent]]>>=
if(parent && parent->flags&LEAF){
    fprint(STDERR, "newpanel: can't create child of %s %lux\n", 
             parent->kind, (ulong)parent);
    exits("bad newpanel");
}
@


\subsection{Widget-specific data}
\label{sec:widget-data}

%claude:
Each widget type needs its own private state:
a label stores a string, a button stores a callback, a text entry
stores an editable buffer.
Rather than using a C union (which would make [<Panel>] grow with
every new widget type), [[libpanel]] uses a [[void *data]] pointer
and a separate [[free]] method.
The constructor allocates [[ndata]] bytes for the widget's private
structure, and each widget type casts [[data]] to its own type
(e.g., [[LabelData *]]).

<<[[Panel]] widget-specific data>>=
// union<ref_own<Label|Entry|Button|...>
void *data;					/* kind-specific data */
@

<<[[Panel]] other methods>>=
void (*free)(Panel *);				/* free fields of data when done */
@


<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set widget-specific data fields>>=
if(ndata)
    v->data=pl_emalloc(ndata);
else
    v->data=nil;
v->free=nil;
@
% ndata is a parameter of [[pl_newpanel()]] and usually a sizeof(WidgetXxx)

%claude:
Note the order: the widget's [[free]] method is called before
[[free(p->data)]], because the method may need to access
[[data]] to release its own resources (e.g., freeing strings
stored inside a [[LabelData]]).

<<[[plfree()]] free the widget-specific data>>=
if(p->free)
    p->free(p);
if(p->data)
    free(p->data);
@
% order important here!

\subsection{Widget display state}

% The widgets is displayed differently if it's clicked on or not.
% For example text entry, or button.
% Moreover the reaction is different depending on the previous state
% of the widget.
%claude:
Widgets can be in different visual states --- for example, a button
looks different when pressed ([[DOWN]]) versus released ([[UP]]).
The [[state]] field tracks this so that the widget can be drawn
differently depending on whether it is active or not,
and so that mouse event handling can toggle between states.

<<[[Panel]] other fields>>=
// enum<Style>
int state;					/* for hitting & drawing purposes */
@

% internal DS. Defined in pldefs.h not panel.h
<<enum [[Style]]>>=
/*
 * States, also styles
 */
enum{
    // for text entries, buttons
    UP,
    DOWN,
    <<[[Style]] other cases>>
};
@


\subsection{Main widget methods}

%claude:
Here is the {object-oriented programming in~C} at the heart of
[[libpanel]]: each widget has three function pointers that act
as {virtual methods}.
[[draw]] paints the widget,
[[hit]] handles mouse events,
and [[type]] handles keyboard events.
%
Each widget constructor (e.g., [<pllabel()>], [<plbutton()>])
fills in these pointers with its own implementation.
The default values are error-raising stubs set by [<pl_newpanel()>],
so forgetting to initialize them is caught immediately.

<<[[Panel]] main methods>>=
void (*draw)(Panel *);				/* draw panel and children */

bool (*hit)(Panel *, Mouse *);			/* process mouse event */
void (*type)(Panel *, Rune);			/* process keyboard event */
@
% bool for hit return if need to send next mouse event to
% same widget (see [[REMOUSE]])


<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set default methods>>=
v->draw=pl_drawerror;
v->hit=pl_hiterror;
v->type=pl_typeerror;
@
% See error management appendix. raise error. 
% The widget specific constructor should set those fields correctly!


%\subsection{Scrolling fields}
% later

%\section{Keyboard focus}
%later the [[plkbfocus]] global


\section{[[Icon]]}

%claude:
Many widgets need to display content that could be either
text or a bitmap image --- a button might show a label string or
an icon graphic, and the programmer should not have to use
a different widget type for each case.
%
The [<Icon>] type solves this with a simple trick:
[[typedef void]] makes [[Icon *]] a generic pointer that can hold
either an [[Image *]] or a [[char *]],
with [<pl_drawicon()>] dispatching at runtime.
This lets widgets like buttons and labels accept either text or image
content through the same interface.

<<type [[Icon]]>>=
typedef void Icon;			/* Always used as Icon * -- Image or char */
@

% see pl_drawicon()

\section{Layout styles}
\label{sec:layout-styles}

%claude:
Layout in [[libpanel]] is controlled by three orthogonal sets of flags,
all stored in the [[flags]] field of [<Panel>]:
{packing} determines which side of the parent a widget is attached to
(north, south, east, west),
{placement} determines where within its allocated space the widget
sits (centered, or pushed to a corner),
and {filling} determines whether the widget expands to fill
available space horizontally or vertically.
%
This is directly inspired by Tk's {packer} geometry manager
(see Chapter~\ref{chap:layout}).
The flags are encoded as bit fields in a single [[int]],
so they can be combined with bitwise OR.

\subsection{Placement}

%claude:
Placement controls where a widget sits within the space allocated
to it by the packer.
By default, widgets are centered ([[PLACECEN]]).
The compass directions ([[PLACEN]], [[PLACES]], [[PLACEE]], [[PLACEW]]
and corners) push the widget to an edge or corner of its allocated rectangle.

<<constant [[PLACE]]>>=
#define	PLACE	0x01e0		/* which side of its space should the Panel adhere to? */
@
% bitmask?

<<constant [[PLACECEN]]>>=
#define		PLACECEN 0x0000
@
%Center, default if nothing set.

<<constant [[PLACES]]>>=
#define		PLACES	0x0020
@
<<constant [[PLACEE]]>>=
#define		PLACEE	0x0040
@
<<constant [[PLACEW]]>>=
#define		PLACEW	0x0060
@
<<constant [[PLACEN]]>>=
#define		PLACEN	0x0080
@
<<constant [[PLACENE]]>>=
#define		PLACENE	0x00a0
@
<<constant [[PLACENW]]>>=
#define		PLACENW	0x00c0
@
<<constant [[PLACESE]]>>=
#define		PLACESE	0x00e0
@
<<constant [[PLACESW]]>>=
#define		PLACESW	0x0100
@
\l why skip one letter each time?

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
      PLACENW       PLACEN       PLACENE
     +----------+  +----------+  +----------+
     |[w]       |  |   [w]    |  |       [w]|
     |          |  |          |  |          |
     |          |  |          |  |          |
     +----------+  +----------+  +----------+

      PLACEW       PLACECEN      PLACEE
     +----------+  +----------+  +----------+
     |          |  |          |  |          |
     |[w]       |  |   [w]    |  |       [w]|
     |          |  |          |  |          |
     +----------+  +----------+  +----------+

      PLACESW       PLACES       PLACESE
     +----------+  +----------+  +----------+
     |          |  |          |  |          |
     |          |  |          |  |          |
     |[w]       |  |   [w]    |  |       [w]|
     +----------+  +----------+  +----------+
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Packing}

% Difference with place? This is to say how multiple children widgets
% relate to each other.
%claude:
Packing determines which side of the parent a widget is attached to
and, by extension, how sibling widgets divide the available space.
When a widget is packed to the north ([[PACKN]]), it takes a
horizontal strip from the top of the remaining space;
when packed to the east ([[PACKE]]), it takes a vertical strip
from the right.
This is the same algorithm as Tk's [[pack]] command.

<<constant [[PACK]]>>=
#define	PACK	0x0007		/* which side of the parent is the Panel attached to? */
@
% bitmask

<<constant [[PACKN]]>>=
#define		PACKN	0x0000
@
%Default

<<constant [[PACKE]]>>=
#define		PACKE	0x0001
@

<<constant [[PACKS]]>>=
#define		PACKS	0x0002
@

<<constant [[PACKW]]>>=
#define		PACKW	0x0003
@


<<constant [[PACKCEN]]>>=
#define		PACKCEN	0x0004	/* only used by pulldown */
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
   Parent space                PACKN then PACKN        PACKN then PACKE
  +-------------+            +-------------+          +-------------+
  |             |            |  [widget A] |          |  [widget A] |
  |             |            +-------------+          +------+------+
  |             |            |  [widget B] |          |      |[B]  |
  |             |            +-------------+          |      |     |
  |             |            | (remaining) |          | rest |     |
  +-------------+            +-------------+          +------+------+
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Filling}

%claude:
Filling controls whether a widget grows to fill its allocated space.
[[FILLX]] makes the widget expand horizontally,
[[FILLY]] makes it expand vertically,
and both can be combined.
Without these flags, a widget only takes up its ``natural'' size
(as reported by [<pl_sizereq()>]).
[[EXPAND]] is stronger: it makes the widget claim all
\emph{extra} space in the parent, useful for making one widget
(like a text area) grow while others (like buttons) stay fixed.

<<constant [[FILLX]]>>=
#define	FILLX	0x0008		/* grow horizontally to fill the available space */
@

<<constant [[FILLY]]>>=
#define	FILLY	0x0010		/* grow vertically to fill the available space */
@


<<constant [[EXPAND]]>>=
#define	EXPAND	0x0200		/* use up all extra space in the parent */
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
   No FILL              FILLX               FILLY            FILLX|FILLY
  +----------+       +----------+       +----------+       +----------+
  |          |       |          |       | [widget] |       |[widget   |
  | [widget] |       |[widget  ]|       | [      ] |       |[         |
  |          |       |          |       | [      ] |       |[         |
  +----------+       +----------+       +----------+       +----------+
  widget stays        stretches          stretches          stretches
  at natural size     horizontally       vertically         both ways
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Padding}

% user settable
%claude:
Padding adds extra space around a widget:
[[pad]] is the external padding (space between this widget and its
neighbors), and [[ipad]] is the internal padding (space between
the widget's border and its content).
Both are [[Vector]] (i.e., [[Point]]) values, giving independent
horizontal and vertical padding.

<<[[Panel]] padding fields>>=
Vector ipad;				/* extra space inside and outside */
Vector pad;
@
% see panel.pdf

<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set other fields>>=
v->ipad=Pt(0,0);
v->pad=Pt(0,0);
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  +------------------------------------------+
  |              pad (external)               |
  |   +----------------------------------+   |
  |   |          ipad (internal)         |   |
  |   |   +--------------------------+   |   |
  |   |   |        content           |   |   |
  |   |   +--------------------------+   |   |
  |   +----------------------------------+   |
  +------------------------------------------+
\end{verbatim}

%\section{Box styles}
% meh

\section{[[Direction]]}

%claude:
Scrollbars and sliders can be oriented horizontally or vertically.

<<enum [[Direction]]>>=
/*
 * Scrollbar, slider orientations
 */
enum Direction {
    HORIZ,
    VERT
};
@
%pad: I named it


%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Initialization}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:main}

%claude:
Before any widget can be drawn, [[libpanel]] needs to allocate
a set of shared color images used throughout the library for
drawing borders, backgrounds, and highlights.
This is done once at startup by [<plinit()>].

\section{[[plinit()]]}

%init.c
<<function [[plinit]]>>=
/*
 * Just a wrapper for all the initialization routines
 */
error0 plinit(int ldepth){
    return pl_drawinit(ldepth);
}
@
%old: I simplified and just call pl_drawinit

%claude:
The actual work is in [<pl_drawinit()>] below, which allocates
five shared [[Image]] values: black, white, dark, light, and
a highlight mask.
These are used by all widgets for drawing 3D-effect borders
(light on top-left, dark on bottom-right) and selection highlights.

<<global [[plldepth]]>>=
static int plldepth;
@

<<globals [[pl_xxx]]>>=
static Image *pl_white, *pl_light, *pl_dark, *pl_black, *pl_hilit;
@

%draw.c
<<function [[pl_drawinit]]>>=
error0 pl_drawinit(int ldepth){

    plldepth=ldepth;

    pl_black=allocimage(display, Rect(0,0,1,1), view->chan, 1, 0x000000FF);
    pl_white=allocimage(display, Rect(0,0,1,1), view->chan, 1, 0xFFFFFFFF);

    pl_dark =allocimage(display, Rect(0,0,1,1), view->chan, 1, DPurpleblue);
    pl_light=allocimagemix(display, DPalebluegreen, DWhite);

    pl_hilit=allocimage(display, Rect(0,0,1,1), CHAN1(CAlpha,8), 1, 0x80);

    if(pl_white==nil || pl_light==nil || pl_black==nil || pl_dark==nil) 
        return ERROR_0;
    return OK_1;
}
@

% nice allocimagemix! (See \book{Graphics}).

% pl_hilit: it's a mask. used to draw highlight on selected item in lists
%claude:
Note [[pl_hilit]]: it is not a color but an alpha mask (50\%
transparency), used to draw translucent highlights over
selected items in lists.

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Drawing}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:drawing}

%claude:
Drawing in [[libpanel]] is a recursive walk down the widget tree:
starting from the root, each widget draws itself using its
[[draw]] method, then its children are drawn on top.
The rest of this chapter covers the shared drawing helpers
that widgets use to render borders and boxes.

\section{[[pldraw()]]}

%see hellopanel.c:
%    pldraw(root, view);
% so get passed [[view]] in [[b]] below.

% main -> eresized | ... -> <>
%claude:
The entry point [<pldraw()>] takes the root widget and the
destination [[Image *b]] (typically [[view]], the screen).
It delegates to [<pl_draw1()>] and then flushes the
display to make the result visible.

<<function [[pldraw]]>>=
void pldraw(Panel *p, Image *b){
    pl_draw1(p, b);
    flushimage(display, true);
}
@

%claude:
The [[flushimage()]] call and the [[display]] global are part of
\plan's graphics system, explained in the \book{Graphics}.

% can also be called in some hit callback to draw related widgets
% for example if have a slider and label, when you move the slider
% you want to update and then redraw the label (you could also
% simply decide to redraw all from the root).
%claude:
[<pl_draw1()>] is the version without the final [[flushimage()]],
useful when a [[hit]] callback needs to redraw a sibling widget
(e.g., updating a label after a slider moves) without flushing twice.

<<function [[pl_draw1]]>>=
void pl_draw1(Panel *p, Image *b){
    if(b!=nil)
        pl_drawall(p, b);
}
@

%claude:
[<pl_drawall()>] is the recursive core: it stores the drawing
surface in [[p->b]], calls the widget's [[draw]] method,
then recurses on each child.
Every widget in the tree ends up sharing the same [[Image *b]]
(the screen), drawing into its own [[p->r]] rectangle within it.

<<function [[pl_drawall]]>>=
void pl_drawall(Panel *p, Image *b){
    <<[[pl_drawall()]] if invisible widget>>
    p->b=b;
    // widget-specific method
    p->draw(p);
    for(p=p->child;p;p=p->next)
        // recurse
        pl_draw1(p, b);
}
