%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Events}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:events}

%claude:
Event dispatch is the other half of the widget library (drawing being
the first).
The application's event loop receives raw mouse and keyboard events
from \plan's event system, then calls [<plmouse()>] or
[<plkeyboard()>] to route them to the right widget.

\section{Mouse events}

% called in event loop with root widget as first parameter
% (see hellopanel.c)

% <event user loop> -> <>
%claude:
[<plmouse()>] is called from the application's event loop
with the root widget and a [[Mouse]] event.
It finds which leaf widget contains the mouse position
using [<pl_ptinpanel()>], then calls that widget's [[hit]] method.
It also tracks which widget received the last event
([[lastmouse]]) so it can send an [[OUT]] notification
when the mouse moves to a different widget.

<<function [[plmouse]]>>=
void plmouse(Panel *g, Mouse *m){
    Panel* hit;
    Panel* last = g->lastmouse;
    bool remouse;

    <<[[plmouse()]] if [[REMOUSE]] set [[hit]] to [[last]]>>
    else{
        hit=pl_ptinpanel(m->xy, g);
        if(last && last!=hit){
            <<[[plmouse()]] when [[last!=hit]] send [[OUT]] mouse event>>
        }
    }
    if(hit){
        // widget-specific method
        remouse=hit->hit(hit, m);
        <<[[plmouse()]] handle [[remouse]]>>
        g->lastmouse=hit;
    }
    flushimage(display, true);
}
@
%pad: I introduced remouse local and set last earlier
\l why panel called g?

<<[[Panel]] other fields>>=
Panel *lastmouse;				/* who got the last mouse event? */
@
<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set other fields>>=
v->lastmouse=nil;
@
% But this is really used only for the root panel?

%claude:
[<pl_ptinpanel()>] walks the widget tree to find the deepest
(most leafward) widget whose rectangle contains the mouse point.
When a child and its parent both contain the point, the one with
higher {priority} wins --- this is how popup menus can intercept
events even when they overlap other widgets.

<<function [[pl_ptinpanel]]>>=
/*
 * Return the most leafward, highest priority panel containing p
 */
Panel *pl_ptinpanel(Point p, Panel *g){
    Panel *v;

    for(;g;g=g->next) 
      if(ptinrect(p, g->r)){
        //recurse
        v=pl_ptinpanel(p, g->child);

        if(v && v->pri(v, p) >= g->pri(g, p)) 
            return v;
        else
            return g;
      }
    return nil;
}
@

% How handle popup menu that goes beyond parent widget? the rectangle
%  of parent widget is extended?
% No, see example in libpanel manual; the popup is a parent of the text area,
% but the parent has higher priority of the child, so even if point inside
%  child, then it's the parent that will get the event (and it can redispatch
%  the event to one of its children).

%dup: g->r is set by plpack()

\subsection{Mouse leaving the widget}

%claude:
When the mouse moves from one widget to another, the old widget
needs to know --- for example, a button should redraw itself in
the [[UP]] state.
Rather than adding a separate ``mouse leave'' method,
[[libpanel]] reuses the [[hit]] method with an extra [[OUT]] bit
set in [[Mouse.buttons]].
Since \plan mice have three buttons (bits 0--2), bit~3 is free.

<<constant [[OUT]]>>=
/*
 * An extra bit in Mouse.buttons
 */
#define	OUT	8			/* Mouse.buttons bit, set when mouse leaves Panel */
@
% m->buttons is a bitsets with 3 bits (LMR) so bit 4 is free

<<[[plmouse()]] when [[last!=hit]] send [[OUT]] mouse event>>=
m->buttons|=OUT;
last->hit(last, m);
m->buttons&=~OUT;
@

\subsection{[[REMOUSE]]}

%claude:
Sometimes a widget needs to keep receiving mouse events even after
the cursor leaves its rectangle --- for example, when dragging a
scrollbar thumb.
The [[hit]] method signals this by returning [[true]], which sets
the [[REMOUSE]] flag on the root widget.
On the next event, [<plmouse()>] skips [<pl_ptinpanel()>] and
sends the event directly to the same widget.

<<constant [[REMOUSE]]>>=
#define	REMOUSE	0x40000		/* send next mouse event here, even if not inside */
@

% some hit method will return true, meaning they want the next
% mouse event (so hit will be lastmouse, not the in pl_ptinpanel().

<<[[plmouse()]] handle [[remouse]]>>=
if(remouse)
    g->flags|=REMOUSE;
else
    g->flags&=~REMOUSE;
@

<<[[plmouse()]] if [[REMOUSE]] set [[hit]] to [[last]]>>=
if(g->flags&REMOUSE)
    hit=last;
@
%pad: I factorized g->lastmouse in earlier setting of local last

\subsection{Hitting priority}

%claude:
The [[pri]] method is another virtual method on [<Panel>],
returning an integer priority for hit testing.
Most widgets use [[PRI_NORMAL]] (0).
Popup menus use [[PRI_POPUP]] (1) so they receive events
even when overlapping lower-priority children.
Scrollbars use [[PRI_SCROLLBAR]] (2) because they sit at the edge
of their parent and must win over the content area.

<<[[Panel]] other methods>>=
int (*pri)(Panel *, Point);			/* priority for hitting */
@

<<constant [[PRI_NORMAL]]>>=
