\section{Keyboard events}

%claude:
Keyboard events are simpler than mouse events: there is a single
global {keyboard focus} widget ([[plkbfocus]]), and all keyboard
events go to it.
Focus is set implicitly by mouse interaction --- only widgets
that accept text input (text entries, text editors) call
[<plgrabkb()>] in their [[hit]] method to claim the focus.
Widgets that do not handle keyboard input (labels, buttons,
scrollbars) simply never call it.


<<global [[plkbfocus]]>>=
Panel *plkbfocus;			/* the panel in keyboard focus */
@

% some mouse hitting function will set plkbfocus so the next keyboard
% event are sent to the same widget.

% pl_hitentry | pl_hitedit -> <>
<<function [[plgrabkb]]>>=
void plgrabkb(Panel *g){
    plkbfocus=g;
}
@
% the hitting function of a widget will set this widget
% to have the focus for the next keyboard event.




% <user code> -> <>
%claude:
[<plkeyboard()>] is called from the application's event loop
with a [[Rune]] (a Unicode character, see \book{Libcore}).
If a widget has the focus, its [[type]] method is called.
The [[flushimage()]] afterwards ensures that any visual changes
(e.g., a new character appearing in a text entry) are
immediately displayed.

<<function [[plkeyboard]]>>=
void plkeyboard(Rune c){
    if(plkbfocus){
        // widget-specific callback
        plkbfocus->type(plkbfocus, c);
        flushimage(display, true);
    }
}
@

% A rune! See \book{Libcore}

%claude:
When a widget is freed, the focus must be cleared if it
pointed to that widget, otherwise [<plkeyboard()>] would
dereference a dangling pointer.

<<[[plfree()]] if [[plkbfocus]]>>=
if(p==plkbfocus)
    plkbfocus=nil;
@

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Layout}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:layout}

%claude:
Layout is a two-pass process.
The first pass, [<pl_sizereq()>], walks the tree {bottom-up}:
each widget computes how much space it needs, based on its
content and its children's requests.
The second pass, [<pl_setrect()>], walks the tree {top-down}:
starting from the available window rectangle, each widget
is assigned an actual position and size, and the remaining
space is divided among its children according to the packing flags.

% eresized -> <>
%claude:
The entry point [<plpack()>] runs both passes in sequence.
It is called from [[eresized()]] with [[view->r]] as the
available rectangle.

<<function [[plpack]]>>=
void plpack(Panel *p, Rectangle where){
    pl_sizereq(p);
    pl_setrect(p, where.min, subpt(where.max, where.min));
}
@
% called with [[view->r]] for [[where]] in hellopanel.c

% called plpack() but it is not just for packing, it's really
% for the whole layout.
%claude:
Note that [<pl_setrect()>] takes a point and a size vector
([[where.min]] and [[subpt(where.max, where.min)]]) rather than
a [[Rectangle]].
This is because the recursive algorithm needs to manipulate
the origin ([[ul]]) and available space ([[avail]]) independently
--- advancing [[ul]] and shrinking [[avail]] as each child is
packed --- which is more natural with separate point/vector
arithmetic than with rectangle operations.

% Two steps: estimate size, and then set actual rectangles for everybody. 
\l Need two steps?


\section{Layout fields}

% Saw layout DS (flags) before.
%claude:
Each widget stores three size-related vectors.
[[sizereq]] is the total space the widget requests (children +
own decoration + padding).
[[childreq]] is the combined size of all children (computed by
[<pl_sizesibs()>]).
[[size]] is the final allocated size after the top-down pass
adjusts for available space, filling, and expansion.

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  sizereq (bottom-up, what we want):
  +--------------------------------------+
  | pad                                  |
  |  +--------------------------------+  |
  |  | ipad                           |  |
  |  |  +--getsize(childreq)-------+  |  |
  |  |  | decoration (e.g. border) |  |  |
  |  |  |  +----childreq--------+  |  |  |
  |  |  |  | children combined  |  |  |  |
  |  |  |  +--------------------+  |  |  |
  |  |  +------ = sizereq ---------+  |  |
  |  |        before padding           |  |
  |  +--------------------------------+  |
  +--------------------------------------+

  size (top-down, what we get):
  - starts from sizereq
  - minus pad (external padding not included)
  - clamped to avail (if not enough space)
  - expanded to avail (if FILLX/FILLY set)
\end{verbatim}

<<[[Panel]] layout fields>>=
Vector sizereq;					/* size requested by this Panel */
Vector childreq;					/* total size needed by children */
@
% sizereq is childreq + extra size for enclosing widget + inside and outside
%  padding
% req for requested.

<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set other fields>>=
v->sizereq=Pt(0,0);
@
% forgot to set childreq too?



<<[[Panel]] layout fields>>=
Vector size;					/* space for this Panel */
@
% size is 
%  - smaller than sizereq by pad (external pad)
%  - smaller if no available space compared to what was requested.
%  - bigger if set EXPAND

<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set other fields>>=
v->size=Pt(0,0);
@

% will see packing methods soon.

% FIGURE relating those fields.

\section{Computing sizes: [[pl_sizereq()]]}

% Step 1.
%claude:
The bottom-up pass first recurses into all children, then
computes [[childreq]] by combining the children's sizes
according to their packing direction (via [<pl_sizesibs()>]),
and finally asks the widget itself how much space it needs
around its children (via the [[getsize]] method).
Padding is added last.

<<function [[pl_sizereq]]>>=
/*
 * Compute the requested size of p and its descendants.
 */
void pl_sizereq(Panel *p){
    Panel *cp;
    <<[[pl_sizeref()]] other locals>>

    for(cp=p->child;cp;cp=cp->next){
        // recurse
        pl_sizereq(cp);
        <<[[pl_sizeref()]] when looping over children, adjust [[maxsize]]>>
    }
    <<[[pl_sizereq()]] if [[MAXX]] or [[MAXY]]>>
    p->childreq=pl_sizesibs(p->child);
    // widget-specific method
    p->sizereq=p->getsize(p, p->childreq);
    <<[[pl_sizereq()]] adjust size with padding>>
    <<[[pl_sizereq()]] if [[FIXEDX]] or [[FIXEDY]]>>
}
@
%pad: I added p->sizereq=p->getsize(p, p->childreq); that was
% done with the padding adjustment before in one instruction


<<[[Panel]] packing methods>>=
Vector (*getsize)(Panel *, Vector);		/* return size, given child size */
@
<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set default methods>>=
v->getsize=pl_getsizeerror;
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  pl_sizereq(parent):

  1. recurse into children        2. combine children     3. add own decoration
                                     (pl_sizesibs)           (getsize + padding)

  child A: sizereq = 40x20       childreq = 40x50        sizereq = 44x56
  child B: sizereq = 30x30           (PACKN: max width,     (+2 border
              ^                        sum heights)           +2 ipad + pad)
              |
         (recursed first)
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Packing}

%claude:
[<pl_sizesibs()>] combines sibling sizes according to their
packing direction.
Siblings packed north/south stack vertically: their widths
are maxed and their heights are summed.
Siblings packed east/west stack horizontally: the opposite.
This is a recursive walk over the sibling list.

<<function [[pl_sizesibs]]>>=
Vector pl_sizesibs(Panel *p){
    Vector s;

    <<[[pl_sizesibs()]] if no panel>>
    // recurse
    s=pl_sizesibs(p->next);

    switch(p->flags&PACK){
    <<[[pl_sizesibs()]] switch packing flags cases>>
    }
    return s;
}
@


<<[[pl_sizesibs()]] if no panel>>=
if(p==nil) 
    return Pt(0,0);
@
% pl_sizesibs() is called with p->child and most widgets do not have children so
% this is not a sanity check but a base case.


<<[[pl_sizesibs()]] switch packing flags cases>>=
case PACKN:
case PACKS:
    s.x=pl_max(s.x, p->sizereq.x);
    s.y+=p->sizereq.y;
    break;
@
%FIGURE
% when pack on top of each other, width is max and height must be added.
%dup: Note that PACKN is 0 so this is the default case if the user
% did not specify any packing flags when adding multiple widgets in a parent.

% We do not care about placement flags here. Just the packing flags
% are useful.

<<[[pl_sizesibs()]] switch packing flags cases>>=
case PACKE:
case PACKW:
    s.x+=p->sizereq.x;
    s.y=pl_max(s.y, p->sizereq.y);
    break;
@
%FIGURE

<<function [[pl_max]]>>=
int pl_max(int a, int b){
    return a>b ? a : b;
}
@
\l replace by MAX macro?

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  PACKN/PACKS (vertical stacking)     PACKE/PACKW (horizontal stacking)

  +--------+  width = max(A,B)        +----+----+  width = A.x + B.x
  |   A    |  height = A.y + B.y      |    |    |  height = max(A,B)
  +--------+                          | A  | B  |
  |   B    |                          |    |    |
  +--------+                          +----+----+
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Padding}

%ipad and pad are user-defined hooks.

<<[[pl_sizereq()]] adjust size with padding>>=
p->sizereq=addpt(addpt(p->sizereq, p->ipad), p->pad);
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  sizereq after getsize():      sizereq after padding:
  +------------------+          +------------------------+
  |  widget content  |          | pad                    |
  |  + children      |    -->   |  +------------------+  |
  +------------------+          |  | ipad             |  |
    getsize(childreq)           |  |  +-----------+   |  |
                                |  |  | content   |   |  |
                                |  |  +-----------+   |  |
                                |  +------------------+  |
                                +------------------------+
\end{verbatim}

\section{Computing rectangles: [[pl_setrect()]]}

% Step 2.

%    pl_setrect(p, where.min, subpt(where.max, where.min));
%claude:
The top-down pass takes an upper-left point ([[ul]]) and available
space ([[avail]]) and assigns [[p->r]].
The steps are: start from the requested size, subtract external
padding, clamp to available space, expand if [[FILLX]]/[[FILLY]]
flags are set, adjust [[ul]] for placement, set [[p->r]],
then recurse into children with the remaining interior space.

<<function [[pl_setrect]]>>=
/*
 * Set the sizes and rectangles of p and its descendants, given their requested sizes.
 */
void pl_setrect(Panel *p, Point ul, Vector avail){
    <<[[pl_setrect()]] locals>>

    // setting p->size
    p->size=p->sizereq;
    <<[[pl_setrect()]] reduce size for external padding>>
    <<[[pl_setrect()]] reduce size if bigger than available>>
    <<[[pl_setrect()]] expand size if fill or expand flags>>

    // setting ul
    <<[[pl_setrect()]] adjust origin with placement>>

    // setting p->r
    p->r=Rpt(ul, addpt(ul, p->size));

    // recurse
    <<[[pl_setrect()]] setting the rectangle of the children>>
}
@
%pad: I added the p->size=p->sizereq instead of doing it
% also while padding

%Finally set [[p->r]]!!

% Note that this time we recurse after setting the property of
% the parent (before we were recursing before) because the parent here
% will decide where to place the children (but the children were
% specifying their size independently)

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  pl_setrect(p, ul, avail):

  ul                          ul (adjusted)
  +--avail-----------+        +--avail-----------+
  |                  |        | pad/2            |
  |                  |   -->  |  +--size------+  |
  |                  |        |  |  p->r      |  |
  |                  |        |  +------------+  |
  +------------------+        +------------------+
                              then recurse into children
                              within p->r interior
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Padding}

<<[[pl_setrect()]] reduce size for external padding>>=
p->size=subpt(p->sizereq, p->pad);
ul=addpt(ul, divpt(p->pad, 2));
avail=subpt(avail, p->pad);
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  Before padding:               After padding:
  ul                            ul' = ul + pad/2
  +----avail----------+         +----avail'-------+
  |                   |         |  +--size------+ |
  |  size = sizereq   |   -->   |  |            | |
  |                   |         |  +------------+ |
  +-------------------+         +-----------------+
                                  size = sizereq - pad
                                  avail' = avail - pad
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Filling}

<<[[pl_setrect()]] reduce size if bigger than available>>=
if(p->size.x>avail.x)
    p->size.x = avail.x;
if(p->size.y>avail.y)
    p->size.y = avail.y;
@

<<[[pl_setrect()]] expand size if fill or expand flags>>=
if(p->flags&(FILLX|EXPAND)) 
    p->size.x=avail.x;
if(p->flags&(FILLY|EXPAND)) 
    p->size.y=avail.y;
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  No flags:              FILLX:               FILLX|FILLY:
  +----avail------+     +----avail------+     +----avail------+
  |               |     |               |     |[size=========]|
  |  [size]       |     |[size=========]|     |[             ]|
  |               |     |               |     |[             ]|
  +---------------+     +---------------+     +---------------+
  size unchanged        size.x = avail.x     size = avail
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Placing}

<<[[pl_setrect()]] adjust origin with placement>>=
switch(p->flags&PLACE){
case PLACECEN:	ul.x+=(avail.x-p->size.x)/2; ul.y+=(avail.y-p->size.y)/2; break;
case PLACES:	ul.x+=(avail.x-p->size.x)/2; ul.y+= avail.y-p->size.y   ; break;
case PLACEE:	ul.x+= avail.x-p->size.x   ; ul.y+=(avail.y-p->size.y)/2; break;
case PLACEW:	                             ul.y+=(avail.y-p->size.y)/2; break;
case PLACEN:	ul.x+=(avail.x-p->size.x)/2;                              break;
case PLACENE:	ul.x+= avail.x-p->size.x   ;                              break;
case PLACENW:   /** Nothing **/                                           break;
case PLACESE:	ul.x+= avail.x-p->size.x   ; ul.y+= avail.y-p->size.y   ; break;
case PLACESW:                                ul.y+= avail.y-p->size.y   ; break;
}
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  PACKN: child A takes top strip, then B takes next strip

  ul                           newul
  +----space----------+        +----newspace------+
  |  child A (PACKN)  |        |  child B         |
  +-------------------+   -->  |  ...             |
  |  remaining space  |        +------------------+
  +-------------------+
     avail for A:                 space shrinks by A's height
     (space.x, A.sizereq.y)
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Packing the children}

<<[[pl_setrect()]] locals>>=
Panel *c;
Vector space;
Point newul;
Vector newspace;
@

%claude:
The child loop allocates space from the parent's interior.
For each child, based on its packing direction, it carves out
a strip (horizontal or vertical) for the child and recurses,
then advances [[ul]] and shrinks [[space]] for the next sibling.
The [[childspace]] method lets the widget adjust the starting
point and available space (e.g., a frame shrinks the interior
to account for its border).

<<[[pl_setrect()]] setting the rectangle of the children>>=
space=p->size;
// widget-specific adjustment method
p->childspace(p, &ul, &space);

<<[[pl_setrect()]] before looping over children, set locals>>
for(c=p->child;c;c=c->next){
    <<[[pl_setrect()]] when looping over children, if [[EXPAND]] flag>>
    switch(c->flags&PACK){
    <<[[pl_setrect()]] when looping over children, switch packing cases>>
    }
    ul=newul;
    space=newspace;
}
@


%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  Without childspace:            With childspace (frame):
  ul                             ul' (shifted inward)
  +----space----------+          +----space----------+
  |                   |          | frame border       |
  |  children fill    |          |  +--space'------+  |
  |  entire space     |          |  | children     |  |
  |                   |          |  +--------------+  |
  +-------------------+          +-------------------+
\end{verbatim}

<<[[Panel]] packing methods>>=
/* child ul & size given our size */
void (*childspace)(Panel *, Point * /**INOUT**/, Vector * /**INOUT**/);
@
% Most of the time empty an empty method doing nothing.
% Defined just once for the frame to adjust ul and space used for the frame
% so children have actually less space than enclosing widget (for
% space used by the frame)

<<[[pl_newpanel()]] set default methods>>=
v->childspace=pl_childspaceerror;
@


% recurse!
%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  PACKN: child at top              PACKS: child at bottom
  ul                               ul (unchanged = newul)
  +----space.x--------+            +----space.x--------+
  |  child (at ul)    |            |                   |
  +-------------------+ <- newul   |  remaining space  |
  |  remaining space  |            +-------------------+
  |  (newspace)       |            |  child (at bottom)|
  +-------------------+            +-------------------+
\end{verbatim}

<<[[pl_setrect()]] when looping over children, switch packing cases>>=
case PACKN:
    newul=Pt(ul.x, ul.y+c->sizereq.y);
    newspace=Pt(space.x, space.y-c->sizereq.y);
    pl_setrect(c, ul, Pt(space.x, c->sizereq.y));
    break;
case PACKS:
    newul=ul;
    newspace=Pt(space.x, space.y-c->sizereq.y);
    pl_setrect(c, Pt(ul.x, ul.y+space.y-c->sizereq.y),
        Pt(space.x, c->sizereq.y));
    break;
@

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  PACKW: child at left             PACKE: child at right
  ul         newul                 ul (unchanged = newul)
  +----+-------------+            +-------------+----+
  |    |             |            |             |    |
  | ch |  remaining  |            |  remaining  | ch |
  |    |  (newspace) |            |  (newspace) |    |
  +----+-------------+            +-------------+----+
\end{verbatim}

<<[[pl_setrect()]] when looping over children, switch packing cases>>=
case PACKW:
    newul=Pt(ul.x+c->sizereq.x, ul.y);
    newspace=Pt(space.x-c->sizereq.x, space.y);
    pl_setrect(c, ul, Pt(c->sizereq.x, space.y));
    break;
case PACKE:
    newul=ul;
    newspace=Pt(space.x-c->sizereq.x, space.y);
    pl_setrect(c, Pt(ul.x+space.x-c->sizereq.x, ul.y),
        Pt(c->sizereq.x, space.y));
    break;
@


\subsubsection{Expanding child}

%XXX
%claude:
When children have the [[EXPAND]] flag, the leftover space
([[slack]] = available minus total requested) is distributed
among them.
[<pl_getshare()>] counts how many children want to expand in
each direction, and each one gets an equal fraction of the slack.
The division is done incrementally (dividing the remaining slack
by the remaining count) to handle rounding without losing pixels.

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  Before EXPAND:                 After EXPAND (2 children, both EXPAND):
  +-----space=100------+         +-----space=100------+
  |  A (req 30) PACKN  |         |  A (30+20=50) PACKN|
  +--------------------+         +--------------------+
  |  B (req 30) PACKN  |         |  B (30+20=50) PACKN|
  +--------------------+         +--------------------+
  |  slack = 40        |            slack distributed evenly:
  +--------------------+            40 / 2 = 20 each
\end{verbatim}

<<[[pl_setrect()]] locals>>=
Vector slack, share;
int l;
@

<<[[pl_setrect()]] before looping over children, set locals>>=
slack=subpt(space, p->childreq);
share=pl_getshare(p->child);
@

<<[[pl_setrect()]] when looping over children, if [[EXPAND]] flag>>=
if(c->flags&EXPAND){
    switch(c->flags&PACK){
    case PACKN:
    case PACKS:
        c->sizereq.x+=slack.x;
        l=slack.y/share.y;
        c->sizereq.y+=l;
        slack.y-=l;
        --share.y;
        break;
    case PACKE:
    case PACKW:
        l=slack.x/share.x;
        c->sizereq.x+=l;
        slack.x-=l;
        --share.x;
        c->sizereq.y+=slack.y;
        break;
    }
}
@

<<function [[pl_getshare]]>>=
Point pl_getshare(Panel *p){
    Point share;

    if(p==nil) 
        return Pt(0,0);

    // recurse
    share=pl_getshare(p->next);

    if(p->flags&EXPAND) {
        switch(p->flags&PACK){
        case PACKN:
        case PACKS:
            if(share.x==0) share.x=1;
            share.y++;
            break;
        case PACKE:
        case PACKW:
            share.x++;
            if(share.y==0) share.y=1;
            break;
        }
    }
    return share;
}
@

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Basic Widgets}
\label{chap:basic-widgets}
%******************************************************************************

%trans: seen main functions. draw and pack used in hellopanel.c
% now go through all widgets in more details.
%toc:
% Each time init/draw/react/pack/ methods.

% No children, always have LEAF set.
% There are other LEAF widgets in other sections, but those are really
% the basic one.

%claude:
Now that we have seen the core infrastructure (data structures,
drawing, events, layout), we can look at the individual widgets.
This chapter covers the basic {leaf} widgets: labels, text entries,
and buttons.
They all have the [[LEAF]] flag set and cannot have children.
%
Each widget follows the same pattern: a private data structure
(e.g., [<Label>], [<Entry>], [<Button>]),
a constructor that calls [<pl_newpanel()>] and fills in the
methods,
and implementations of [[draw]], [[hit]], [[type]], [[getsize]],
and [[childspace]].

\section{Label}

%example: see hellopanel.c
%claude:
A label is the simplest widget: it just displays an [<Icon>]
(text or image) inside a passive border.
Its private data stores only the icon and a placement direction
for positioning the content within the label's rectangle.

<<struct [[Label]]>>=
struct Label{
    // enum<Placement> (default = PLACECEN)
    int placement;
    // ref_own<Icon> = ref_own<Image|string> depending on Panel.flags&BITMAP
    Icon *icon;
};
@

<<constant [[BITMAP]]>>=
#define	BITMAP	0x4000		/* text argument is a bitmap, not a string */
@
% flags passed to pllabel(), and assigned to Panel.flags in plinitlabel()

\subsection{Initializing}

<<function [[pllabel]]>>=
Panel *pllabel(Panel *parent, int flags, Icon *icon){
    Panel *p;

    p=pl_newpanel(parent, sizeof(Label));
    plinitlabel(p, flags, icon);
    plplacelabel(p, PLACECEN);
    return p;
}
@
% place center

<<function [[plinitlabel]]>>=
void plinitlabel(Panel *v, int flags, Icon *icon){
    Label* l = v->data;

    v->flags=flags|LEAF;

    v->draw=pl_drawlabel;
    v->hit=pl_hitlabel;
    v->type=pl_typelabel;

    v->getsize=pl_getsizelabel;
    v->childspace=pl_childspacelabel;

    l->icon=icon;
    //l->placement set in plplacelabel()

    v->kind="label";
}
@

%claude:
Recall that [[v->data]] was already allocated by [<pl_newpanel()>]
with [[sizeof(Label)]] bytes, so [<plinitlabel()>] can cast it
directly to [[Label *]] and fill in the fields.
The [[kind]] field is a string used for debugging messages
(see the Debugging appendix) --- it was already referenced
by the error message in [<pl_newpanel()>].

% pllabel | <user code> -> <>
<<function [[plplacelabel]]>>=
void plplacelabel(Panel *p, int placement){
    Label* l = p->data;

    l->placement=placement;
}
@

\subsection{Drawing}

%claude:
Drawing a label is straightforward: draw a [[PASSIVE]] box (light
background, thin border), with [<pl_box()>] (which internally
calls [<pl_boxoutline()>]), then draw the icon inside it using
the label's placement setting.

<<function [[pl_drawlabel]]>>=
void pl_drawlabel(Panel *p){
    Label *l = p->data;

    pl_drawicon(p->b, pl_box(p->b, p->r, PASSIVE), 
                l->placement, p->flags, l->icon);
}
@

<<[[Style]] other cases>>=
// for labels
PASSIVE,
@
% abused by pl_box() but not really set in Panel.state

%claude:
The [[PASSIVE]] case of [<pl_boxoutline()>] (defined in
Chapter~\ref{chap:drawing}) is shown here because this is
where it is first used.
In literate programming, definition chunks can be spread
across multiple chapters --- [[noweb]] collects all the
[[pl\_boxoutline() switch style cases]] chunks and assembles
them into a single switch statement.

<<[[pl_boxoutline()]] switch style cases>>=
case PASSIVE:
    if(fill) 
        draw(b, r, pl_light, 0, ZP);
    r=insetrect(r, PWID);
    if(!fill) 
        border(b, r, SPACE, pl_white, ZP);
    break;
@

<<constant [[PWID]]>>=
#define	PWID	1	/* width of label border */
@



%claude:
[<pl_drawicon()>] is the shared helper that actually renders an
[<Icon>] (text or bitmap) inside a rectangle.
It computes the offset needed to position the icon according to
the [[stick]] placement, adjusts the clip rectangle to avoid
drawing outside the widget's bounds, then calls either
[[draw()]] (for bitmaps) or [[string()]] (for text).

<<function [[pl_drawicon]]>>=
void pl_drawicon(Image *b, Rectangle r, int stick, int flags, Icon *s){
    Point ul;
    Vector offs;
    <<[[pl_drawicon()]] other locals>>

    ul=r.min;
    offs=subpt(subpt(r.max, r.min), pl_iconsize(flags, s));

    switch(stick){
    <<[[pl_drawicon()]] switch placement cases, adjust [[ul]]>>
    }

    <<[[pl_drawicon()]] save and adjust clip rectangle>>
    if(flags&BITMAP) 
        draw(b, Rpt(ul, addpt(ul, pl_iconsize(flags, s))), s, nil, ZP);
    else 
        string(b, ul, pl_black, ZP, font, s);
    <<[[pl_drawicon()]] restore saved clip rectangle>>
}
@
% flags just passed down for the BITMAP thing I think


%dup: can now use [[p->r]]! packing has been done, and
% p->b has been set in caller in pl_draw() (actually in pl_drawall())



% text is black

<<function [[pl_iconsize]]>>=
Vector pl_iconsize(int flags, Icon *p){
    if(flags&BITMAP) 
        return subpt(((Image *)p)->r.max, ((Image *)p)->r.min);
    else 
        return stringsize(font, (char *)p);
}
@


<<[[pl_drawicon()]] switch placement cases, adjust [[ul]]>>=
case PLACENW:	/** Nothing **/                 break;
case PLACEN:	ul.x+=offs.x/2;                 break;
case PLACENE:	ul.x+=offs.x;                   break;
case PLACEW:	                ul.y+=offs.y/2; break;
case PLACECEN:	ul.x+=offs.x/2; ul.y+=offs.y/2; break;
case PLACEE:	ul.x+=offs.x;                   break;
case PLACESW:	                ul.y+=offs.y;   break;
case PLACES:	ul.x+=offs.x/2; ul.y+=offs.y;   break;
case PLACESE:	ul.x+=offs.x;   ul.y+=offs.y;   break;
@
%FIGURE?

<<[[pl_drawicon()]] other locals>>=
Rectangle save;
@
<<[[pl_drawicon()]] save and adjust clip rectangle>>=
save=b->clipr;
if(!rectclip(&r, save))
    return;
replclipr(b, b->repl, r);
@
<<[[pl_drawicon()]] restore saved clip rectangle>>=
replclipr(b, b->repl, save);
@
% need clipping just for string()?

\subsection{Reacting}

% no reaction for labels
%claude:
Labels do not react to mouse or keyboard events --- the methods
are no-ops.

<<function [[pl_hitlabel]]>>=
bool pl_hitlabel(Panel *p, Mouse *m){
    USED(p, m);
    return false;
}
@

<<function [[pl_typelabel]]>>=
void pl_typelabel(Panel *p, Rune c){
    USED(p, c);
}
@

\subsection{Packing methods}

<<function [[pl_getsizelabel]]>>=
Vector pl_getsizelabel(Panel *p, Vector children){
    USED(children);		/* shouldn't have any children */
    return pl_boxsize(pl_iconsize(p->flags, ((Label *)p->data)->icon), 
                      PASSIVE);
}
@

<<[[pl_boxsize()]] switch state cases>>=
case PASSIVE:
    return addpt(interior, Pt(2*(PWID+SPACE), 2*(PWID+SPACE)));
@
% [[2*]] because there is on the left and right (and top and bottom)
%  and we use insetrect in many places
% then for PWID see pl_boxoutline for PASSIVE and 
% then for SPACE because done for all pl_box() (see end of pl_boxoutline).

%claude:
The [[childspace]] method is called by [<pl_setrect()>] during
layout (see Chapter~\ref{chap:layout}) to let the widget adjust
the interior space available for its children.
Since a label is a [[LEAF]] widget and has no children, this is
a no-op.

<<function [[pl_childspacelabel]]>>=
void pl_childspacelabel(Panel *g, Point *ul, Vector *size){
    USED(g, ul, size);
}
@
% no adjustments



\section{Text entry}

%example: ?
%claude:
A text entry is a single-line editable field.
Its private data stores the text buffer ([[entry]]),
a pointer to the current end of text ([[entp]]),
a pointer to the end of the allocated buffer ([[eent]]),
a minimum display size, and a callback for when the user
presses Enter.

<<struct [[Entry]]>>=
struct Entry{
    // ref_own<string>
    char *entry;
    <<[[Entry]] pointer in [[entry]] fields>>
    Vector minsize;

    void (*hit)(Panel *, char *);
};
@

<<[[Entry]] pointer in [[entry]] fields>>=
// point to \0 in entry
char *entp;
// point to end of entry
char *eent;
@

\subsection{Initializing}

<<function [[plentry]]>>=
Panel *plentry(Panel *parent, int flags, int wid, char *str, void (*hit)(Panel *, char *)){
    Panel *v;

    v=pl_newpanel(parent, sizeof(Entry));
    plinitentry(v, flags, wid, str, hit);
    return v;
}
@


<<function [[plinitentry]]>>=
void plinitentry(Panel *v, int flags, int wid, char *str, void (*hit)(Panel *, char *)){
    Entry *ep = v->data;
    int elen;

    v->flags=flags|LEAF;

    v->draw=pl_drawentry;
    v->hit=pl_hitentry;
    v->type=pl_typeentry;

    v->getsize=pl_getsizeentry;
    v->childspace=pl_childspaceentry;

    <<[[plinitentry()]] set snarf methods>>
    <<[[plinitentry()]] set extra fields>>
    <<[[plinitentry()]] set fields in [[ep]]>>

    v->free=pl_freeentry;

    v->kind="entry";
}
@

<<function [[pl_freeentry]]>>=
void pl_freeentry(Panel *p){
    Entry *ep = p->data;

    free(ep->entry);
    ep->entry = ep->eent = ep->entp = nil;
}
@


<<[[plinitentry()]] set fields in [[ep]]>>=
ep->minsize=Pt(wid, font->height);

elen=100;
if(str) 
    elen+=strlen(str);
ep->entry=pl_erealloc(ep->entry, elen+SLACK);

ep->eent=ep->entry+elen;
strecpy(ep->entry, ep->eent, str ? str : "");
ep->entp=ep->entry+strlen(ep->entry);

ep->hit=hit;
@
% note that eent is not using SLACK

% why pl_erealloc? because can recall plinitentry later?

<<constant [[SLACK]]([[(lib_gui/libpanel/textwin.c)]])>>=
#define SLACK 100
@
% you just need 4 I think, that is the maxsize of a rune in
% number of bytes

\subsection{Drawing}

%claude:
The entry is drawn with an [[UP]] box when unfocused and a [[DOWN]]
box when focused (clicked).
The [[UP]] style has a light background with a raised border;
[[DOWN]] reverses the relief to look sunken, signaling that the
widget is active and accepting input.
%
The text is aligned to the left ([[PLACEW]]) if it fits,
or to the right ([[PLACEE]]) if it overflows, so the end
of the text (where the user is typing) stays visible.

<<[[plinitentry()]] set extra fields>>=
v->state=UP;
@
% UP and then DOWN
% box of entry changes depending if has focus

<<function [[pl_drawentry]]>>=
void pl_drawentry(Panel *p){
    Entry *ep = p->data;
    char *s = ep->entry;
    Rectangle r;

    r=pl_box(p->b, p->r, p->state);

    <<[[pl_drawentry]] if [[USERFL]]>>
    if(stringwidth(font, s) <= r.max.x-r.min.x)
        pl_drawicon(p->b, r, PLACEW, NOFLAG, s);
    else
        pl_drawicon(p->b, r, PLACEE, NOFLAG, s);
    <<[[pl_drawentry]] when [[USERFL]] if [[s]] changed>>
}
@
% aligned on the right, unless too big in which case displays
% the beginning of the text.

<<[[pl_boxoutline()]] switch style cases>>=
case UP:
    pl_relief(b, pl_white, pl_black, r, BWID);
    r=insetrect(r, BWID);
    if(fill) 
        draw(b, r, pl_light, nil, ZP);
    else 
        border(b, r, SPACE, pl_white, ZP);
    break;
@

<<constant [[BWID]]>>=
#define	BWID	1	/* width of button relief */
@


% will see soon than displayed differently if entry is clicked on
% in which case the state of the widget becomes DOWN.
<<[[pl_boxoutline()]] switch style cases>>=
case DOWN:
case DOWN1:
case DOWN2:
case DOWN3:
    pl_relief(b, pl_black, pl_white, r, BWID);
    r=insetrect(r, BWID);
    if(fill) 
        draw(b, r, pl_dark, 0, ZP);
    else 
        border(b, r, SPACE, pl_black, ZP);
    break;
@
% reverse relief effect, shadow is now at the top

% black on pl_dark this time.

\subsubsection{Drawing secret text}

%claude:
When a text entry is used for passwords, the actual characters
should not be visible on screen.
If the application sets the [[USERFL]] flag on the entry,
the drawing code replaces every character with [['*']] before
rendering.
The internal buffer is unchanged --- only the display is masked.

<<constant [[USERFL]]>>=
#define USERFL	0x100000	/* start of user flag */
@

<<[[pl_drawentry]] if [[USERFL]]>>=
if(p->flags & USERFL){
    char *p;
    s=strdup(s);
    for(p=s; *p; p++)
        *p='*';
}
@
<<[[pl_drawentry]] when [[USERFL]] if [[s]] changed>>=
if(s != ep->entry)
    free(s);
@
% replace text entry content with stars, just for displaying

\subsection{Reacting}

% changes [[Panel.state]]!
%claude:
When the user clicks on a text entry, the [[hit]] method
switches the state to [[DOWN]], grabs the keyboard focus
with [<plgrabkb()>], and enters a tight loop consuming mouse
events until the button is released.
The loop is needed because while the left button is held,
a middle or right click triggers copy/paste operations
(snarf and paste, see Chapter~\ref{chap:advanced}).
Without the loop, those chord clicks would be lost.

<<function [[pl_hitentry]]>>=
bool pl_hitentry(Panel *p, Mouse *m){
    if((m->buttons&7)==CLICK_LEFT){
        p->state=DOWN;
        plgrabkb(p);
        // redraw with changed state
        pldraw(p, p->b);

        while(m->buttons&CLICK_LEFT){
            int old = m->buttons;
            // next mouse event
            *m=emouse();
            <<[[pl_hitentry()]] handle copy/paste when middle or right click>>
        }
        // redraw with changed state
        p->state=UP;
        pldraw(p, p->b);
    }
    return false;
}
@

%plgrabkb()!

% wait until release left click

% Once widget has focus, every key will go there if user event loop
% calls plkeyboard().
%claude:
The [[type]] method handles keyboard input: Enter triggers the
callback, printable characters are appended to the buffer
(with automatic reallocation if needed), and backspace erases
the last rune.

<<function [[pl_typeentry]]>>=
void pl_typeentry(Panel *p, Rune c){
    Entry *ep = p->data;
    int n;

    switch(c){
    <<[[pl_typeentry()]] switch rune cases>>
    }
    // draw updated entry
    pldraw(p, p->b);
}
@


<<[[pl_typeentry()]] switch rune cases>>=
case '\n':
case '\r':
    *ep->entp='\0';
    if(ep->hit) 
        ep->hit(p, ep->entry);
    return;
@
% useful to set again ep->entp? is should already be [[\0]]

<<[[pl_typeentry()]] switch rune cases>>=
